INSERT INTO `naac_content` VALUES (1,'Which specific national policies advocated for the establishment of an independent national accreditation agency for higher education in India?','The establishment of an independent national accreditation agency like NAAC was strongly advocated by the National Policy on Education (NPE), 1986 and the Programme of Action (PoA),  These policy documents emphasized the need for maintaining quality in higher education and recommended setting up an autonomous accreditation body to assess and ensure standards across institutions.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(2,'In what year was NAAC established, and what is its status in relation to the University Grants Commission (UGC)?','NAAC was established in the year 1994. It is an autonomous institution of the University Grants Commission (UGC). This means that while it operates independently in terms of assessment and accreditation processes, it functions under the umbrella of UGC.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(3,'Where is the headquarters of the National Assessment and Accreditation Council located?','The headquarters of NAAC is located in Bengaluru (Bangalore), India.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(4,'Who serves as the President of the General Council (GC) of NAAC?','The Chairperson of the University Grants Commission (UGC) serves as the President of the General Council (GC) of NAAC.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(5,'How is the Chairperson of the Executive Committee (EC) of NAAC selected?','The Chairperson of the Executive Committee (EC) is nominated by the President of the General Council, who is the UGC Chairperson. This ensures leadership alignment with national higher education policies.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(6,'What are the dual responsibilities of the Director of NAAC regarding its governing bodies?','The Director of NAAC acts as the Member-Secretary of both the General Council (GC) and Executive Committee (EC) and is responsible for the administrative and academic functioning of NAAC.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(7,'What factors in the Indian education system led to widespread concerns regarding the quality and relevance of higher education?','Rapid expansion of institutions, privatization, diversification of programmes, and increased access without adequate quality assurance mechanisms led to concerns regarding quality and relevance of higher education.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(8,'What is the formal vision statement of NAAC regarding the defining element of higher education in India?','The vision of NAAC is to make quality the defining element of higher education in India through a combination of self and external quality evaluation, promotion and sustenance initiatives.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(9,'What are the three pillars (evaluation, promotion, and sustenance) through which NAAC aims to achieve its vision?','NAAC achieves its vision through quality evaluation, quality promotion, and quality sustenance initiatives.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(10,'Which mission statement specifically addresses the stimulation of the academic environment for teaching-learning and research?','The mission includes arranging for periodic assessment and accreditation of institutions and programmes, which stimulates improvement in teaching-learning and research environments.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(11,'How does NAAC\'s mission aim to encourage accountability and innovations within Higher Education Institutions (HEIs)?','NAAC encourages accountability and innovation by promoting autonomy, self-evaluation, quality-related research, and adoption of innovative practices in academic and administrative processes.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(12,'With which entities does NAAC seek to collaborate for quality evaluation and sustenance according to its mission?','NAAC collaborates with stakeholders of higher education including institutions, government bodies, industry, and other agencies for quality evaluation and sustenance.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(13,'What type of academic activities does NAAC undertake directly as part of its engagement and endeavor?','NAAC undertakes research studies, consultancy, training programmes, workshops, and quality enhancement initiatives.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(14,'What are the five core values that form the foundation for the assessment of institutions volunteering for NAAC accreditation?','The five core values are contributing to national development, fostering global competencies among students, inculcating a value system among students, promoting the use of technology, and quest for excellence.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(15,'How does the manual define the role of HEIs in Contributing to National Development?','HEIs contribute by developing human resources, promoting social justice, supporting economic development, and addressing societal needs.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(16,'What specific student attributes are targeted under the value of Fostering Global Competencies?','The focus is on developing global awareness, communication skills, adaptability, employability, and understanding of global trends.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(17,'Why does NAAC emphasize Inculcating a Value System among students even when skill development is high?','Because technical skills alone are not sufficient; students must also develop ethical values, social responsibility, and moral integrity for holistic development.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(18,'What specific administrative and academic functions should be technology-enabled to meet the core value of Promoting the Use of Technology?','Teaching-learning, administration, evaluation processes, data management, and communication systems should be technology-enabled.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(19,'How does the Quest for Excellence value relate to the preparation of the Self-Study Report (SSR)?','It reflects institutional self-evaluation, continuous improvement, identification of strengths and weaknesses, and commitment to quality enhancement through SSR preparation.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(20,'Are institutions permitted to add their own unique core values to the five provided by NAAC?','Yes, institutions can add their own core values provided they align with NAAC’s vision and mission.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(21,'How does the NAAC framework reconcile universal core values with the National context?','NAAC adapts universal quality values to suit Indian cultural diversity, socio-economic conditions, and national educational priorities.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(22,'What was the explicit Paradigm Shift introduced in the Revised Assessment and Accreditation Framework launched in July 2017?','The revised framework introduced a major paradigm shift from a predominantly qualitative peer-judgement model to a data-based quantitative indicator evaluation model. It emphasizes transparency, objectivity, and benchmarking, and makes greater use of ICT. It also introduces pre-qualification criteria, enhanced student participation through SSS, and a stronger focus on learning outcomes.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(23,'How does the revised framework use benchmarking as a tool for quality improvement?','The revised framework defines clear performance benchmarks for all quantitative metrics. Institutions can compare their performance with national standards, identify gaps, and adopt improvement strategies. Benchmarking promotes consistency and quality enhancement across institutions.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(24,'What is the role of third-party validation of data in the current assessment process?','All quantitative data submitted by institutions undergo Data Validation and Verification (DVV) by a third-party agency appointed by NAAC. This ensures authenticity, eliminates false claims, and increases credibility in the assessment process.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(25,'How has the revised manual changed the participation of students and alumni in the assessment process?','The revised manual includes direct student participation through the Student Satisfaction Survey (SSS) and considers alumni feedback as part of the quality indicators. This makes the process more participatory and inclusive.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(26,'What are the three main components that comprise the total assessment process?','The three main components are: Self-Study Report (SSR) submitted by the institution, Student Satisfaction Survey (SSS), and Peer Team Visit (PTV) for validation and qualitative assessment.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(27,'What is the approximate percentage distribution between Quantitative Metrics (QnM) and Qualitative Metrics (QlM)?','Quantitative Metrics carry approximately 70% weightage, while Qualitative Metrics carry about 30% of the total score in the revised assessment framework.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(28,'How many total metrics are autonomous colleges required to address in their Self-Study Report (SSR)?','Autonomous colleges must respond to 85 metrics in total, which include both quantitative and qualitative metrics.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(29,'Which of the seven criteria carries the highest total weightage (300 points) for autonomous colleges?','Criterion II – Teaching-Learning and Evaluation carries the highest weightage of 300 points, reflecting the centrality of academic processes.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(30,'In Criterion I (Curricular Aspects), which Key Indicator is applicable only to Universities and Autonomous Colleges, but not to Affiliated Colleges?','Key Indicator 1 – Curriculum Design and Development is applicable only to Universities and Autonomous Colleges, as they have academic autonomy. Affiliated colleges follow the curriculum designed by their affiliating universities.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(31,'What is the Pre-qualifier score required for an institution to proceed to the Peer Team Visit?','The institution must score at least 25% of the total Quantitative Metrics (QnM) score to qualify for the Peer Team Visit. Failure to achieve this results in termination of the assessment process.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(32,'What happens to an institution\'s application if they do not clear the Pre-qualifier stage?','If an institution fails the pre-qualifier stage, the process is terminated and the institution must reapply for assessment after a period of six months. The submitted fees are forfeited.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(33,'Within how many days must the Data Validation and Verification (DVV) process be completed by NAAC?','The DVV process must be completed within 30 days from the date of receiving the required data and clarifications from the institution.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(34,'What is the validity period for a successful NAAC accreditation?','A successful NAAC accreditation is valid for a period of five years from the date of declaration of results.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(35,'Under what conditions can the validity period be extended from five to seven years?','Institutions accredited in their third or fourth cycle with the highest grade may receive an extension of validity from five to seven years, provided they maintain quality standards.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(36,'How is the Student Satisfaction Survey conducted, and when does it occur in the timeline?','The SSS is conducted online by NAAC through student email IDs provided by the institution. It is conducted after SSR submission and forms part of the assessment process.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(37,'What is the minimum response rate required from students for the SSS to be considered valid for a college?','For the SSS to be valid, a minimum of 10% of the total student population or at least 100 students (whichever is lesser) must respond.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(38,'How many objective and subjective questions are included in the SSS questionnaire?','The SSS consists of 20 objective questions and 1 subjective question, focusing on teaching-learning processes.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(39,'What is the typical duration and size of the Peer Team for an onsite visit?','A typical Peer Team consists of 2 to 5 members and the visit usually lasts 2 to 3 days, depending on the size and nature of the institution.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(40,'How many days before the visit are the details of the Peer Team members disclosed to the institution?','The details of the Peer Team members are shared with the institution three days prior to the visit.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(41,'What are the key activities carried out during the Peer Team Visit (PTV)?','During the Peer Team Visit, the team verifies the data submitted in the SSR, interacts with stakeholders such as students, faculty, alumni, and management, inspects infrastructure and facilities, reviews documents, and evaluates institutional practices. The visit ensures validation of claims and provides qualitative assessment.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(42,'What is the outcome of the Peer Team Visit in terms of reporting?','The Peer Team prepares a Peer Team Report (PTR) which includes observations, strengths, weaknesses, and recommendations. This report forms an important component in final accreditation grading.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(43,'How is the final grade awarded to an institution after the assessment process?','The final grade is awarded based on the Cumulative Grade Point Average (CGPA) calculated from the scores of all criteria, including QnM, QlM, and SSS components.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(44,'What are the CGPA ranges for NAAC grades?','A++: 51–00, A+: 26–50, A: 01–25, B++: 76–00, B+: 51–75, B: 01–50, C: 51–00, D: ≤50 (Not Accredited).','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(45,'What does a D grade indicate in NAAC accreditation?','A D grade indicates that the institution is not accredited, as it has scored less than or equal to 50 CGPA.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(46,'What is the significance of Institutional Information for Quality Assessment (IIQA)?','IIQA is the first step in the accreditation process. It verifies the eligibility of the institution before SSR submission and ensures that only qualified institutions proceed further.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(47,'What are the key eligibility requirements for submitting IIQA?','Institutions must have at least two batches of graduates, affiliation or recognition from competent authorities, compliance with UGC/AICTE norms, and minimum years of establishment as specified by NAAC.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(48,'What happens if the IIQA is rejected?','If IIQA is rejected, the institution must resubmit after making necessary corrections, and a revised fee may be applicable.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(49,'What is the purpose of the Self-Study Report (SSR)?','SSR is a comprehensive document prepared by the institution that presents its performance across all NAAC criteria, including strengths, weaknesses, and quality initiatives.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(50,'What are the seven criteria used in NAAC accreditation?','The seven criteria are Curricular Aspects, Teaching-Learning and Evaluation, Research, Innovations and Extension, Infrastructure and Learning Resources, Student Support and Progression, Governance, Leadership and Management, and Institutional Values and Best Practices.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(51,'What is the importance of Criterion II in NAAC assessment?','Criterion II focuses on the core academic processes, including teaching-learning methods, student evaluation, faculty quality, and learning outcomes. It carries the highest weightage.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(52,'What does Criterion III emphasize?','Criterion III emphasizes research activities, innovation practices, extension programs, and collaboration with external organizations.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(53,'What aspects are covered under Criterion IV?','Criterion IV covers physical infrastructure, library resources, IT facilities, and maintenance of academic and support facilities.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(54,'What is the focus of Criterion V?','Criterion V focuses on student support services, progression to higher education, placements, scholarships, and extracurricular achievements.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(55,'What does Criterion VI evaluate?','Criterion VI evaluates governance, institutional leadership, strategic planning, financial management, and quality assurance systems.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(56,'What is included in Criterion VII?','Criterion VII includes institutional values, environmental consciousness, gender equity, best practices, and social responsibility initiatives.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(57,'What is the role of Internal Quality Assurance Cell (IQAC)?','IQAC is responsible for continuous quality improvement, documentation, and preparation of the SSR. It acts as a nodal agency for quality assurance.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(58,'What are the key functions of IQAC?','IQAC functions include developing quality benchmarks, facilitating academic and administrative audits, promoting best practices, and preparing Annual Quality Assurance Report (AQAR).','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(59,'What is AQAR and its purpose?','AQAR (Annual Quality Assurance Report) is submitted annually to NAAC to maintain quality standards and track institutional performance after accreditation.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(60,'How does NAAC ensure continuous quality improvement after accreditation?','Through mechanisms like AQAR submission, IQAC functioning, periodic reassessment, and promotion of best practices, NAAC ensures continuous quality improvement.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(61,'What are the seven criteria that represent the core functions and activities of a Higher Education Institution (HEI) within the QIF?','The seven criteria are Curricular Aspects, Teaching-Learning and Evaluation, Research, Innovations and Extension, Infrastructure and Learning Resources, Student Support and Progression, Governance, Leadership and Management, and Institutional Values and Best Practices. These criteria collectively represent the core academic and administrative functions of a Higher Education Institution.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(62,'How many total metrics comprise the QIF for autonomous colleges, and what is the breakdown between QlM and QnM?','The Quality Indicator Framework consists of approximately 85 metrics. Among these, about 70% are Quantitative Metrics (QnM) and 30% are Qualitative Metrics (QlM), ensuring a balance between measurable data and descriptive evaluation.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(63,'How many Key Indicators (KIs) are identified across all seven criteria for autonomous colleges?','There are 34 Key Indicators distributed across the seven criteria, each focusing on specific aspects of institutional performance and quality.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(64,'What is the total weightage (score) assigned to the entire Quality Indicator Framework?','The total weightage assigned to the QIF is 1000 points. This total score is used to calculate the Cumulative Grade Point Average (CGPA) of the institution.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(65,'Which criterion carries the highest weightage (300 points), and how many Key Indicators does it contain?','Criterion II, Teaching-Learning and Evaluation, carries the highest weightage of 300 points. It contains multiple Key Indicators that focus on student admission, learning processes, evaluation, and outcomes.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(66,'What three specific details are provided for each metric in the QIF to help institutions prepare their SSR?','Each metric provides the metric title and number, a detailed description of requirements, and specific data templates along with supporting document requirements for validation.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(67,'What is the total weightage assigned to Criterion I for autonomous colleges, and how is it distributed across its Key Indicators?','Criterion I has a total weightage of 150 points. It is distributed among Curriculum Design and Development, Academic Flexibility, Curriculum Enrichment, and Feedback System.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(68,'How do the curricular responsibilities of autonomous colleges compare to those of affiliated colleges and universities?','Autonomous colleges have the authority to design and revise their curriculum independently. Affiliated colleges follow the curriculum prescribed by universities, while universities have full autonomy in designing and implementing academic programmes.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(69,'What is the main focus of Criterion I in terms of the practices an institution initiates?','Criterion I focuses on curriculum planning, design, implementation, enrichment, and feedback mechanisms to ensure quality education aligned with societal needs.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(70,'What are the four Key Indicators (KIs) identified under Criterion I?','The four Key Indicators are Curriculum Design and Development, Academic Flexibility, Curriculum Enrichment, and Feedback System.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(71,'According to Metric 1, what four levels of developmental needs must the developed curricula address?','The curriculum must address local, regional, national, and global developmental needs to ensure comprehensive relevance.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(72,'Where is an institution required to upload its Programme Outcomes (POs) and Course Outcomes (COs) for public access?','Programme Outcomes and Course Outcomes must be uploaded on the institutional website for transparency and accessibility.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(73,'What are the three specific focus areas for course syllabi mentioned in Metric 2?','The syllabus must emphasize employability, entrepreneurship, and skill development.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(74,'How does the manual describe the process of developing need-based inputs for curriculum design?','The process involves collecting feedback from stakeholders, analysing industry requirements, reviewing global trends, and incorporating academic expertise to design relevant curriculum.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(75,'How does the NAAC manual define Academic Flexibility?','Academic flexibility refers to providing students with options such as choice-based credit systems, interdisciplinary courses, and flexibility in course selection.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(76,'What is the mathematical formula used to calculate the Percentage of new courses introduced?','Percentage of new courses introduced is calculated as (Number of new courses introduced divided by total number of courses) multiplied by','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(77,'What specific meeting minutes must be uploaded as evidence for new courses?','Minutes of Board of Studies and Academic Council meetings approving the introduction of new courses must be uploaded.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(78,'What types of mobility and options are facilitated by academic flexibility?','Academic flexibility facilitates horizontal mobility, interdisciplinary learning, elective choices, and credit transfer opportunities.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(79,'What cross-cutting issues must be integrated into the curriculum?','Professional Ethics, Gender, Human Values, Environment, and Sustainability must be integrated.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(80,'Which national policy and global goals should be integrated into curriculum enrichment?','National Education Policy 2020 and Sustainable Development Goals should be integrated.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(81,'Who are the five categories of stakeholders for feedback?','Students, Teachers, Employers, Alumni, and Academicians.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(82,'What are the five classification options for feedback system?','Category A includes collection, analysis, action taken, and uploading on website. Category B includes action taken and communicated. Category C includes collection and analysis. Category D includes only collection. Category E indicates feedback not collected.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(83,'What minimum documentation is required for feedback validation?','Filled feedback forms, analysis reports, and action taken reports are required.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(84,'Where must feedback reports be hosted?','Feedback reports must be hosted on the institutional website.','ssr','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(85,'What is the total weightage for Criterion I, and what are its Key Indicators?','Criterion I has a total weightage of 150 points. It is divided into four Key Indicators: Curriculum Design and Development (50 points), Academic Flexibility (30 points), Curriculum Enrichment (50 points), Feedback System (20 points).','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(86,'How should an institution demonstrate the relevance of its curricula under Metric 1?','The institution must describe (in max 500 words) how its curricula are developed and implemented to meet local, regional, national, and global developmental needs. This should be reflected in the Programme Outcomes (POs) and Course Outcomes (COs).','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(87,'What is the focus of Metric 2 regarding syllabi revision?','It focuses on whether the programmes offered emphasize employability, entrepreneurship, and skill development. The institution must show that syllabi are adequately revised to incorporate contemporary requirements.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(88,'How is the percentage of new courses calculated and benchmarked for Metric 1?','The metric measures the percentage of new courses introduced out of the total number of courses offered across all programmes during the last five years. Score 4: 20%, Score 3: 15-20%, Score 2: 10-15%, Score 1: 5-10%, Score 0: < 5%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(89,'What cross-cutting issues must be integrated into the curriculum according to Metric 1?','The curriculum should integrate issues relevant to Professional Ethics, Gender, Human Values, Environment, and Sustainability. These should align with the Sustainable Development Goals and National Education Policy – 2020.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(90,'What are the requirements and benchmarks for certificate or value-added courses (Metric 2)?','This metric counts the number of certificate/value-added/Diploma programmes offered (including online courses like MOOCs, SWAYAM, etc.) where students have successfully completed the course in the last five years. Score 4: 50 courses, Score 3: 40-50 courses, Score 2: 20-40 courses, Score 1: 5-20 courses, Score 0: < 5 courses.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(91,'What percentage of programmes must include field projects or internships for a top score in Metric 3?','To receive a score of 4, at least 80% or more of the programmes must have components of field projects, research projects, or internships. The term internship is inclusive of Industry Immersion practices.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(92,'From which stakeholders should the institution obtain structured feedback for Metric 1?','Feedback must be regularly obtained from Students, Teachers, Employers, Alumni, and Academic peers.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(93,'What distinguishes a Category A feedback process from others?','For Category A (Score 4), the institution must demonstrate that feedback is not only collected and analysed but that action has been taken and communicated to relevant bodies, and the feedback reports are hosted on the institutional website. Category B: Action taken and communicated. Category C: Feedback collected and analysed only. Category D: Feedback collected only. Category E: Feedback not collected.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(94,'To achieve the maximum score (4) for Metric 1, what percentage of new courses must be introduced?','The institution must introduce 20% or more new courses out of the total number of courses offered across all programmes during the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(95,'What is the score for an institution that has introduced between 5% and 10% of new courses in the last five years?','An institution introducing between 5% and 10% of new courses receives a score of','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(96,'Under Metric 2, how many certificate, value-added, or diploma programmes must be completed to reach the top benchmark?','The institution reaches a score of 4 if 50 or more such courses/programmes were offered and successfully completed by students within the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(97,'Which specific online platforms are recognised in Metric 2 for curriculum enrichment?','The benchmarks specifically mention MOOCs, SWAYAM, e-PG Pathshala, and NPTEL as valid online course sources.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(98,'What percentage of programmes must include field projects, research projects, or internships to receive a score of 2?','To receive a score of 2, the percentage of programmes with these components must be between 40% and 60%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(99,'How is the Feedback System (Metric 1) graded for an institution that only collects and analyses feedback but does not take further action?','This falls under Category C, which corresponds to a score of','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(100,'What is the difference between Category B and Category A in the feedback process?','Category B (Score 3): Feedback is collected, analysed, and action has been taken and communicated to relevant bodies. Category A (Score 4): Includes everything in Category B, but adds the requirement that the feedback reports must also be hosted on the institutional website.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(101,'Who are the five stakeholder groups from whom structured feedback should be regularly obtained?','Feedback should be obtained from Students, Teachers, Employers, Alumni, and Academic peers.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(102,'What are the specific percentage thresholds for Metric 3 (Field projects/internships)?','Score 4: 80%, Score 3: 60–80%, Score 2: 40–60%, Score 1: 20–40%, Score 0: < 20%','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(103,'In Metric 2, what is the minimum number of certificate or value-added courses needed to avoid a score of 0?','An institution must have at least 5 courses successfully completed by students to receive a score of. Any number below 5 results in a score of 0.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(104,'What are the percentage ranges for scores 1, 2, and 3 regarding the introduction of new courses (Metric 1)?','Score 3: 15–20%, Score 2: 10–15%, Score 1: 5–10%','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(105,'What distinguishes Category D from Category E in the feedback process (Metric 1)?','Category D indicates that feedback is collected, whereas Category E indicates that feedback is not collected at all.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(106,'Under Metric 1, what must happen after feedback is collected and analysed to move from a Score 2 to a Score 3?','The institution must demonstrate that action has been taken and communicated to the relevant bodies.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(107,'What is the final requirement to reach Category A (Score 4) once action has been taken and communicated?','The institution must also ensure that the feedback reports are hosted on the institutional website.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(108,'How is the Enrolment Percentage (Metric 1) calculated and scored?','This metric evaluates the total percentage of students enrolled against the sanctioned seats. Score 4: 90%, Score 3: 80–90%, Score 2: 70–80%, Score 1: 50–70%, Score 0: < 50%','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(109,'What is the minimum enrolment percentage required to receive a score of 3?','To receive a score of 3, the institution must have an enrolment percentage between 80% and 90%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(110,'What specific groups are considered under reserved categories for Metric 2?','The categories include SC, ST, OBC, and others as per the applicable reservation policy of the government.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(111,'What is the period of assessment for the percentage of seats filled against reserved categories?','The metric assesses the percentage of seats filled for first-year admissions during the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(112,'What are the benchmarks for achieving a top score in reserved category admissions?','To achieve a score of 4, the institution must fill 80% or more of the seats reserved for these categories.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(113,'If an institution fills only 45% of its reserved category seats, what score will it receive?','It will receive a score of 1, as the benchmark for that score is between 40% and 50%. Filling less than 40% results in a score of 0.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(114,'What percentage range corresponds to a score of 2 for reserved category enrolment?','A score of 2 is awarded if the percentage of seats filled against reserved categories is between 50% and 70%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(115,'What does the Student-Full-time teacher ratio metric measure?','This metric evaluates the ratio of students to full-time teachers using data from the latest completed academic year.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(116,'What is the required ratio to achieve the maximum score of 4?','To receive a score of 4, the institution must maintain a student-to-teacher ratio of less than 20:1.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(117,'What are the benchmarks for the remaining scores (3 to 0)?','Score 3: 20:1 to 30:1, Score 2: 30:1 to 50:1, Score 1: 50:1 to 60:1, Score 0: 60:1 or greater.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(118,'If an institution has a ratio of 25:1, what score would it be assigned?','It would be assigned a score of 3, as that score covers the range between 20:1 and 30:1.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(119,'What percentage of full-time teachers must be appointed against sanctioned posts to achieve the highest score?','To receive a score of 4, the institution must have 90% or more of its sanctioned posts filled by full-time teachers.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(120,'What are the lower benchmarks for this metric?','Score 3: 80–90%, Score 2: 70–80%, Score 1: 50–70%, Score 0: Less than 50%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(121,'Which advanced degrees are considered when assessing teacher quality in Metric 2?','The assessment includes full-time teachers holding Ph.D., D.Sc., D.Litt., or L.L.D. degrees.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(122,'What is the benchmark for a top score regarding faculty with these advanced degrees?','An institution receives a score of 4 if 70% or more of its full-time teachers hold these degrees.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(123,'How is the Average teaching experience metric calculated?','It is calculated based on the average number of years of experience for full-time teachers, using data only for the latest completed academic year.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(124,'What is the experience requirement for a score of 4?','The average teaching experience must be 15 years or more.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(125,'What are the benchmarks for teaching experience?','Score 3: 12–15 years, Score 2: 9–12 years, Score 1: 6–9 years, Score 0: Less than 6 years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(126,'What does Metric 4 measure regarding teacher longevity?','It measures the percentage of full-time teachers who have been working in the institution throughout the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(127,'What are the benchmarks for teacher retention in this metric?','Score 4: 80%, Score 3: 70–80%, Score 2: 60–70%, Score 1: 50–60%, Score 0: Less than 50%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(128,'How does the institution measure the efficiency of its examination results declaration?','Efficiency is measured by the average number of days from the date of the last semester-end or year-end examination until the final date of result declaration, averaged over the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(129,'What is the benchmark for the fastest declaration of results (Score 4)?','To achieve a score of 4, the institution must declare results in less than 20 days on average.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(130,'What are the scoring benchmarks for longer durations of result declaration?','Score 3: 20–30 days, Score 2: 30–40 days, Score 1: 40–50 days, Score 0: 50 days or more.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(131,'How is the transparency of the evaluation system assessed in Metric 2?','It is assessed based on the percentage of student complaints or grievances regarding evaluation compared to the total number of students who appeared in the examinations during the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(132,'What is the maximum allowable percentage of grievances to receive a top score?','An institution receives a score of 4 if the percentage of evaluation-related complaints is less than 1%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(133,'If an institution has a 7% grievance rate regarding its evaluation process, what score will it be assigned?','It would be assigned a score of 2, which covers the range of 5% to 10%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(134,'What is the total weightage for Criterion I, and what are its Key Indicators?','Criterion I has a total weightage of 150 points. It is divided into four Key Indicators: Curriculum Design and Development (50 points), Academic Flexibility (30 points), Curriculum Enrichment (50 points), Feedback System (20 points).','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(135,'How should an institution demonstrate the relevance of its curricula under Metric 1?','The institution must describe (in max 500 words) how its curricula are developed and implemented to meet local, regional, national, and global developmental needs. This should be reflected in the Programme Outcomes (POs) and Course Outcomes (COs).','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(136,'What is the focus of Metric 2 regarding syllabi revision?','It focuses on whether the programmes offered emphasize employability, entrepreneurship, and skill development. The institution must show that syllabi are adequately revised to incorporate contemporary requirements.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(137,'How is the percentage of new courses calculated and benchmarked for Metric 1?','The metric measures the percentage of new courses introduced out of the total number of courses offered across all programmes during the last five years. Score 4: 20%, Score 3: 15-20%, Score 2: 10-15%, Score 1: 5-10%, Score 0: < 5%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(138,'What cross-cutting issues must be integrated into the curriculum according to Metric 1?','The curriculum should integrate issues relevant to Professional Ethics, Gender, Human Values, Environment, and Sustainability. These should align with the Sustainable Development Goals and National Education Policy – 2020.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(139,'What are the requirements and benchmarks for certificate or value-added courses (Metric 2)?','This metric counts the number of certificate/value-added/Diploma programmes offered (including online courses like MOOCs, SWAYAM, etc.) where students have successfully completed the course in the last five years. Score 4: 50 courses, Score 3: 40-50 courses, Score 2: 20-40 courses, Score 1: 5-20 courses, Score 0: < 5 courses.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(140,'What percentage of programmes must include field projects or internships for a top score in Metric 3?','To receive a score of 4, at least 80% or more of the programmes must have components of field projects, research projects, or internships. The term internship is inclusive of Industry Immersion practices.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(141,'From which stakeholders should the institution obtain structured feedback for Metric 1?','Feedback must be regularly obtained from Students, Teachers, Employers, Alumni, and Academic peers.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(142,'What distinguishes a Category A feedback process from others?','For Category A (Score 4), the institution must demonstrate that feedback is not only collected and analysed but that action has been taken and communicated to relevant bodies, and the feedback reports are hosted on the institutional website. Category B: Action taken and communicated. Category C: Feedback collected and analysed only. Category D: Feedback collected only. Category E: Feedback not collected.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(143,'To achieve the maximum score (4) for Metric 1, what percentage of new courses must be introduced?','The institution must introduce 20% or more new courses out of the total number of courses offered across all programmes during the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(144,'What is the score for an institution that has introduced between 5% and 10% of new courses in the last five years?','An institution introducing between 5% and 10% of new courses receives a score of','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(145,'Under Metric 2, how many certificate, value-added, or diploma programmes must be completed to reach the top benchmark?','The institution reaches a score of 4 if 50 or more such courses/programmes were offered and successfully completed by students within the last five years.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(146,'Which specific online platforms are recognised in Metric 2 for curriculum enrichment?','The benchmarks specifically mention MOOCs, SWAYAM, e-PG Pathshala, and NPTEL as valid online course sources.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(147,'What percentage of programmes must include field projects, research projects, or internships to receive a score of 2?','To receive a score of 2, the percentage of programmes with these components must be between 40% and 60%.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(148,'How is the Feedback System (Metric 1) graded for an institution that only collects and analyses feedback but does not take further action?','This falls under Category C, which corresponds to a score of','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(149,'What is the difference between Category B and Category A in the feedback process?','Category B (Score 3): Feedback is collected, analysed, and action has been taken and communicated to relevant bodies. Category A (Score 4): Includes everything in Category B, but adds the requirement that the feedback reports must also be hosted on the institutional website.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(150,'Who are the five stakeholder groups from whom structured feedback should be regularly obtained?','Feedback should be obtained from Students, Teachers, Employers, Alumni, and Academic peers.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(151,'What are the specific percentage thresholds for Metric 3 (Field projects/internships)?','Score 4: 80%, Score 3: 60–80%, Score 2: 40–60%, Score 1: 20–40%, Score 0: < 20%','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(152,'In Metric 2, what is the minimum number of certificate or value-added courses needed to avoid a score of 0?','An institution must have at least 5 courses successfully completed by students to receive a score of. Any number below 5 results in a score of 0.','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(153,'What are the percentage ranges for scores 1, 2, and 3 regarding the introduction of new courses (Metric 1)?','Score 3: 15–20%, Score 2: 10–15%, Score 1: 5–10%','benchmark','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(154,'What distinguishes Category D from Category E in the feedback process (Metric 1)?','Category D indicates that feedback is collected, whereas Category E indicates that feedback is