 is excluded from infrastructure augmentation.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(439,'What is the minimum financial support amount per faculty member required for attending conferences under Metric 2?','A minimum of Rs. 3000 per faculty per year is required.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(440,'What defines a functional MoU according to Metric 1, and what must happen during the assessment period to qualify it?','A functional MoU is one in which at least one meaningful activity has been conducted during the assessment period. The institution must provide evidence such as reports, dates, number of participants, and nature of collaboration. Without activity, the MoU is not considered valid.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(441,'For environmental and energy audits (Metric 6), what type of organizations are recognized as valid auditing agencies?','Valid agencies include government organizations, recognized auditing bodies, certified professional agencies, and registered NGOs that are authorized to conduct environmental and energy audits.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(442,'What is the requirement for the landing page of a website link provided to document institutional code of ethics or conduct?','The link must lead directly to the specific webpage where the document is hosted. If it redirects only to the homepage, the claim will not be considered valid.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(443,'Why are Field visits or Tours specifically excluded from the percentage of programs with field project components?','Field visits or tours are excluded because they do not involve structured academic work, research components, or evaluation methods like internships or project-based learning.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(444,'What are the five categories of stakeholders from whom structured feedback must be collected?','The five categories are Students, Teachers, Employers, Alumni, and Academic peers.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(445,'What are the specific requirements for the filled-in feedback report used to substantiate claims about curriculum transactions?','Feedback must be collected from all five stakeholder categories, and at least five filled-in feedback forms per category must be submitted. The feedback should focus primarily on curriculum aspects and must be analyzed with supporting documents.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(446,'Why must candidates belonging to reserved categories who are admitted against the General merit category be excluded from Metric 2?','Such candidates are counted under the general merit category and not under reserved quota. Including them in reserved category counts would lead to incorrect representation of reservation data.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(447,'What documentation is required from a Minority Institution to verify its specific reservation policy?','The institution must provide official documents such as government approval or recognition certificate that confirms its minority status and reservation policy.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(448,'For Metric 1, what specific dates must be mentioned in the reports from the Controller of Examination (COE) to calculate the result declaration time?','The report must include the date of the last semester-end examination and the date of result declaration. These dates are used to calculate the number of days taken to declare results.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(449,'How does the rule for calculating result declaration days differ for institutions following a semester system?','In a semester system, only even semester data is considered for calculating result declaration days, ensuring uniformity in evaluation.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(450,'Under Metric 3, why are Best Teacher Awards and Certificates of Appreciation not considered as valid financial support?','These are considered honorary recognitions and do not involve financial assistance for research or academic advancement, hence they are excluded.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(451,'What is the random selection process used by the DVV partner when verifying large data for Ph.D. research scholars (Metric 2)?','When large data is submitted, the DVV partner randomly selects a sample of scholars and verifies their documents such as registration letters and approvals to ensure authenticity.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(452,'What happens to Ph.D. registrations that fall outside the designated five-year assessment period?','Such registrations are excluded and not considered for evaluation.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(453,'How should an institution count awards received for team events in sports or cultural activities (Metric 1)?','Awards received for team events are counted as one award, irrespective of the number of participants.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(454,'Which levels of achievement are specifically avoided in the count of outstanding sports and cultural awards?','Participation or achievements at regional or local levels are not considered. Only inter-university, state, national, or international level achievements are included.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(455,'What form of alumni contribution is explicitly excluded from the financial calculations in Metric 1?','Alumni registration fees are excluded and not considered as contributions.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(456,'What specific financial documents must be certified by a Chartered Accountant to verify alumni contributions?','Audited financial statements showing alumni contributions must be certified by a Chartered Accountant.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(457,'What are the four components an institution must implement regarding its prescribed code of conduct (Metric 10)?','The institution must display the code on its website, form a monitoring committee, organize awareness programs, and ensure implementation of the code of conduct.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(458,'For quality audits on environment and energy (Metric 6), what types of organizations are recognized as valid external auditing agencies?','Government agencies, certified auditing bodies, and recognized NGOs are valid agencies for conducting such audits.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(459,'Under Metric 3, why must an Academic and Administrative Audit (AAA) be conducted only by external experts?','External experts ensure objectivity, transparency, and unbiased evaluation, which cannot be guaranteed by internal audits.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(460,'What type of course changes are specifically excluded from being counted as new courses introduced?','Courses that involve only minor changes without substantial modification in content are excluded.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(461,'What mandatory documentation is required from Academic Council or Board of Studies (BOS) meetings to verify new courses?','Minutes of meetings must clearly mention the introduction of new courses along with approval details.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(462,'How does the SOP define a Course versus a Programme in the context of curricular aspects?','A programme is a degree, while a course is a subject within that programme.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(463,'What is the minimum number of contact hours required for a certificate or value-added course to be considered valid?','A minimum of 30 contact hours is required.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(464,'How should an institution count a value-added course that is repeated multiple times across the five-year assessment period?','Repeated courses should be counted only once during the assessment period.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(465,'Are courses that are already part of the regular curriculum eligible to be counted as Add-on or certificate programs?','No, only additional courses beyond the curriculum are considered.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(466,'What specific evidence must be provided to prove a student successfully completed one of these optional courses?','A course completion certificate issued to the student must be provided.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(467,'Why are Field visits or Tours specifically excluded from the percentage of programs with field project components?','Because they do not involve structured academic evaluation or research work.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(468,'What document must be provided as the Title page for student projects during the DVV clarification process?','The title page must include project title, student name, institution name, and academic year.','SOP','autonomous',NULL,NULL),(469,'What was the historical context for the establishment of NAAC in 1994, and what is its status as an autonomous institution under the UGC?','The National Assessment and Accreditation Council (NAAC) was established in 1994 in response to the growing need for a structured system to evaluate and ensure quality in higher education institutions in India. The rapid expansion of higher education created a demand for accountability, transparency, and continuous improvement. NAAC functions as an autonomous body under the University Grants Commission (UGC), meaning it operates independently in its assessment processes while being supported by the UGC. Its primary role is to assess and accredit institutions based on defined quality parameters, ensuring academic excellence and institutional credibility.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(470,'In which city and state is the NAAC Headquarters located?','The headquarters of NAAC is located in Bengaluru, Karnataka. It serves as the central hub for all accreditation-related activities, including policy implementation, coordination of peer team visits, data validation, and communication with higher education institutions across the country.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(471,'Who serves as the President of the General Council (GC), and who is the designated academic and administrative head of the organisation?','The President of the General Council (GC) is the Chairperson of the University Grants Commission (UGC). The Director of NAAC acts as the chief academic and administrative head of the organization. The Director is responsible for executing policies, managing accreditation processes, and ensuring effective functioning of NAAC.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(472,'Besides the GC and Executive Committee (EC), what other groups are involved in steering NAAC’s policies and activities?','Apart from the General Council and Executive Committee, NAAC involves advisory bodies, peer teams, subject experts, and technical committees. These groups contribute to policy formulation, data validation, peer review, and overall quality assurance, ensuring a transparent and expert-driven accreditation process.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(473,'How does the Vision of NAAC define the role of \"quality\" in Indian higher education?','NAAC’s vision defines quality as a continuous and dynamic process aimed at improving teaching, learning, research, and governance in higher education institutions. It emphasizes that quality is not a one-time achievement but an ongoing effort to meet national and global standards while contributing to societal development.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(474,'What combination of evaluation and promotion initiatives does NAAC use to achieve its institutional vision?','NAAC achieves its vision through a combination of evaluation and promotion strategies. Evaluation includes accreditation, peer team assessment, and data validation, while promotion involves encouraging best practices, innovation, and the establishment of Internal Quality Assurance Cells (IQACs). This ensures both accountability and continuous improvement.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(475,'How many Core Values form the foundation of the NAAC accreditation framework?','The NAAC accreditation framework is based on five core values that guide institutions in achieving comprehensive quality development across academic, administrative, and societal dimensions.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(476,'Contributing to National Development: How is the role of HEIs significant in building human resource capacity to meet the needs of the nation and its economy?','Higher Education Institutions play a crucial role in national development by producing skilled and knowledgeable graduates. They contribute to human resource development by aligning education with industry needs, promoting innovation, and supporting economic growth. They also foster social responsibility and nation-building through education.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(477,'Why is it essential for HEIs to prepare students with internationally-acceptable standards?','It is essential for HEIs to prepare students with internationally acceptable standards to ensure global competitiveness, employability, and adaptability. This helps students perform effectively in diverse international environments and contributes to global knowledge exchange.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(478,'What kind of collaborations and networks are suggested to help students achieve core competencies to face global challenges?','NAAC suggests collaborations with international universities, industries, research organizations, and academic networks. These collaborations include student exchange programs, joint research, internships, and faculty partnerships, which help students gain global exposure and develop competencies required to face global challenges.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(479,'In what ways does NAAC emphasize the importance of inculcating value systems among students?','NAAC emphasizes the importance of inculcating value systems by encouraging institutions to integrate ethical principles, social responsibility, and human values into the curriculum and co-curricular activities. It promotes activities such as community service, environmental awareness programs, and value-based education to ensure that students develop integrity, empathy, and a sense of responsibility towards society.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(480,'What is the significance of promoting the use of technology in higher education institutions?','The promotion of technology in higher education enhances teaching-learning processes, improves access to information, and supports innovative pedagogies. It enables digital learning, online resources, and efficient academic administration. Technology also helps institutions stay relevant in a rapidly evolving global environment and improves the overall quality of education.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(481,'Why does NAAC stress the need for a quest for excellence in higher education?','NAAC stresses the need for a quest for excellence to ensure that institutions continuously improve their academic and administrative performance. Excellence leads to higher standards in education, research, and innovation, helping institutions achieve national and international recognition and contribute effectively to societal development.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(482,'What are the seven criteria used by NAAC to assess higher education institutions?','NAAC assesses institutions based on seven criteria: Curricular Aspects, Teaching-Learning and Evaluation, Research, Innovations and Extension, Infrastructure and Learning Resources, Student Support and Progression, Governance, Leadership and Management, and Institutional Values and Best Practices. These criteria cover all aspects of institutional functioning and quality.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(483,'What is meant by Curricular Aspects in NAAC assessment?','Curricular Aspects refer to the design, development, implementation, and revision of the curriculum. It includes relevance to industry needs, flexibility, academic planning, and the integration of value-added courses and interdisciplinary approaches to enhance student learning.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(484,'What does Teaching-Learning and Evaluation focus on?','This criterion focuses on student enrollment, diversity, teaching methodologies, faculty quality, and evaluation processes. It emphasizes effective teaching practices, continuous assessment, and fair evaluation systems to ensure student learning outcomes are achieved.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(485,'What is covered under Research, Innovations and Extension?','This criterion includes research activities, publications, patents, innovation practices, consultancy, and extension activities. It evaluates how institutions contribute to knowledge creation, societal development, and industry collaboration through research and outreach programs.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(486,'What is the importance of Infrastructure and Learning Resources?','Infrastructure and Learning Resources refer to the availability and maintenance of physical facilities such as classrooms, laboratories, libraries, and IT infrastructure. These resources support effective teaching, learning, and research activities and ensure a conducive academic environment.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(487,'What does Student Support and Progression include?','This criterion includes student welfare measures such as scholarships, career guidance, counseling, placement services, and support for higher education. It also tracks student progression to higher studies and employment, ensuring overall student development.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(488,'What is evaluated under Governance, Leadership and Management?','This criterion evaluates institutional leadership, strategic planning, governance practices, financial management, and quality assurance mechanisms. It ensures that institutions are effectively managed and aligned with their vision and mission.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(489,'What is covered under Institutional Values and Best Practices?','This criterion focuses on the values upheld by the institution and the best practices implemented to ensure holistic development. It includes environmental consciousness, gender equity, inclusiveness, social responsibility, and ethical practices. Institutions are evaluated on how they promote sustainability, inclusivity, and transparency while showcasing unique practices that contribute to quality enhancement.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(490,'What is the process of NAAC accreditation?','The NAAC accreditation process involves several stages, including submission of the Institutional Information for Quality Assessment (IIQA), preparation and submission of the Self-Study Report (SSR), Data Validation and Verification (DVV), Student Satisfaction Survey (SSS), peer team visit, and final accreditation decision. Each stage ensures a comprehensive evaluation of the institution’s quality standards.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(491,'What is Institutional Information for Quality Assessment (IIQA)?','IIQA is the initial step in the NAAC accreditation process where institutions submit basic information about their eligibility and readiness for accreditation. It is a preliminary screening process to determine whether the institution qualifies to proceed with the full assessment.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(492,'What is the Self-Study Report (SSR)?','The Self-Study Report is a comprehensive document prepared by the institution detailing its performance across NAAC’s seven criteria. It includes qualitative and quantitative data, evidence of achievements, and analysis of strengths and weaknesses. The SSR serves as the primary basis for evaluation during the accreditation process.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(493,'What is Data Validation and Verification (DVV)?','DVV is the process through which the data submitted in the SSR is verified for accuracy and authenticity by external experts. This step ensures that the information provided by the institution is reliable and supports fair assessment.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(494,'What is the Student Satisfaction Survey (SSS)?','The Student Satisfaction Survey is conducted by NAAC to collect feedback from students regarding teaching, learning, and institutional facilities. It provides insights into student experiences and contributes to the overall evaluation of the institution.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(495,'What is the role of the peer team visit in NAAC accreditation?','The peer team visit involves a group of experts visiting the institution to validate the SSR, interact with stakeholders, inspect facilities, and assess overall performance. Their observations and evaluations play a crucial role in determining the final accreditation grade.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(496,'How is the final accreditation decision made by NAAC?','The final decision is based on a combination of SSR evaluation, DVV results, SSS feedback, and peer team report. NAAC assigns a cumulative grade point average (CGPA) and corresponding grade to the institution, reflecting its overall quality performance.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(497,'What is CGPA in NAAC accreditation?','CGPA (Cumulative Grade Point Average) is a numerical score assigned to an institution based on its performance across various criteria. It determines the accreditation grade and indicates the overall quality level of the institution.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(498,'What are the different grades awarded by NAAC?','NAAC awards grades such as A++, A+, A, B++, B+, B, and C based on the CGPA obtained by the institution. These grades reflect different levels of quality, with A++ being the highest. Institutions below a certain CGPA may not receive accreditation.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(499,'What is the validity period of NAAC accreditation?','The validity period of NAAC accreditation is typically five years. During this period, the institution is expected to maintain and improve its quality standards. After the validity expires, the institution must apply for re-accreditation to continue its recognized status.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(500,'What is re-accreditation?','Re-accreditation is the process through which an institution undergoes assessment again after the expiry of its previous accreditation. It evaluates the progress made, improvements implemented, and current quality status of the institution.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(501,'What is the Internal Quality Assurance Cell (IQAC)?','The Internal Quality Assurance Cell (IQAC) is a mechanism established within institutions to ensure continuous quality improvement. It plans, monitors, and evaluates quality-related activities and promotes best practices in teaching, learning, and administration.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(502,'What are the functions of IQAC?','IQAC functions include developing quality benchmarks, facilitating the creation of a learner-centric environment, organizing workshops and seminars, collecting feedback, documenting activities, and preparing the Annual Quality Assurance Report (AQAR). It acts as a nodal agency for quality enhancement.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(503,'What is the Annual Quality Assurance Report (AQAR)?','AQAR is a yearly report submitted by institutions to NAAC detailing their quality initiatives, achievements, and improvements. It reflects the ongoing efforts of the institution to sustain and enhance quality in all aspects of functioning.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(504,'What is the role of stakeholders in quality assurance?','Stakeholders such as students, faculty, alumni, employers, and society play a crucial role in quality assurance by providing feedback, participating in decision-making, and supporting institutional development. Their involvement ensures that the institution meets diverse expectations and remains relevant.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(505,'What is the importance of feedback systems in NAAC?','Feedback systems help institutions collect opinions from students, teachers, and other stakeholders regarding curriculum, teaching methods, and facilities. This feedback is analyzed and used to make improvements, ensuring continuous quality enhancement.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(506,'What is meant by best practices in NAAC?','Best practices are innovative and effective methods implemented by institutions that contribute to quality improvement. These practices are documented and shared so that other institutions can adopt and benefit from them.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(507,'What is the significance of institutional distinctiveness?','Institutional distinctiveness refers to the unique features, achievements, or practices that set an institution apart from others. It highlights the institution’s strengths and contributions to society, enhancing its identity and reputation.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(508,'What is quality culture in higher education?','Quality culture refers to the collective commitment of an institution towards continuous improvement in all its activities. It involves participation from all stakeholders, adherence to best practices, and a strong focus on achieving excellence in education and administration.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(509,'What is meant by quality assurance in higher education?','Quality assurance in higher education refers to the systematic processes and practices implemented to ensure that institutions maintain and enhance the standards of teaching, learning, research, and administration. It involves continuous monitoring, evaluation, and improvement to meet defined benchmarks and stakeholder expectations.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(510,'What is quality enhancement in NAAC context?','Quality enhancement is the process of continuously improving institutional performance through innovative practices, feedback mechanisms, and strategic planning. It focuses on strengthening academic and administrative systems to achieve higher standards of excellence.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(511,'What is benchmarking in NAAC?','Benchmarking is the process of comparing institutional performance with established standards or best practices. It helps institutions identify gaps, adopt successful strategies, and improve their overall quality by learning from leading institutions.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(512,'What is academic audit?','An academic audit is a systematic review of academic processes, including curriculum delivery, teaching methods, evaluation practices, and learning outcomes. It ensures that academic standards are maintained and helps identify areas for improvement.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(513,'What is green audit?','A green audit evaluates the environmental practices of an institution, including energy usage, waste management, water conservation, and sustainability initiatives. It ensures that institutions adopt eco-friendly practices and contribute to environmental protection.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(514,'What is gender audit?','A gender audit assesses the institution’s efforts in promoting gender equity and inclusiveness. It examines policies, facilities, safety measures, and participation of all genders to ensure a fair and supportive environment.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(515,'What is energy audit?','An energy audit analyzes the energy consumption patterns of an institution and suggests measures to improve efficiency and reduce wastage. It helps in promoting sustainable energy use and cost savings.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(516,'What is environmental sustainability in NAAC?','Environmental sustainability refers to the institution’s responsibility to minimize environmental impact through practices such as resource conservation, pollution control, waste management, and promotion of green initiatives.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(517,'What is inclusive education?','Inclusive education ensures equal access to education for all students, including those from diverse backgrounds and differently-abled individuals. It promotes diversity, equity, and equal opportunities within the institution.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(518,'What is the role of extension activities in NAAC?','Extension activities involve community engagement programs such as social service, awareness campaigns, and outreach initiatives. They help institutions contribute to societal development and instill social responsibility among students.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(519,'What is the importance of research in higher education institutions?','Research is essential in higher education as it promotes knowledge creation, innovation, and critical thinking. It enhances academic quality, supports evidence-based learning, and contributes to solving real-world problems. Research activities also improve institutional reputation and attract funding and collaborations.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(520,'What are research publications?','Research publications are scholarly articles, papers, or books published in journals, conferences, or other academic platforms. They reflect the research contributions of faculty and students and are an important indicator of academic excellence.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(521,'What is the role of research funding?','Research funding provides financial support for conducting research projects. It enables institutions to acquire resources, carry out experiments, and develop innovative solutions. Funding can come from government agencies, industries, or private organizations.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(522,'What is a research project?','A research project is a systematic investigation undertaken to explore a specific problem or topic. It involves planning, data collection, analysis, and interpretation to generate new knowledge or validate existing theories.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(523,'What are consultancy services in higher education?','Consultancy services involve providing expert advice, technical support, or solutions to industries, organizations, or government bodies. These services help in knowledge transfer, strengthen industry-institution interaction, and generate revenue for the institution.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(524,'What is collaboration in research?','Collaboration in research refers to partnerships between institutions, industries, or international organizations to conduct joint research activities. It enhances the quality of research through shared expertise, resources, and diverse perspectives.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(525,'What is innovation in higher education?','Innovation refers to the introduction of new ideas, methods, or technologies in teaching, learning, and research. It helps institutions improve quality, solve complex problems, and adapt to changing educational and societal needs.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(526,'What are patents?','Patents are legal rights granted to inventors for their innovations, giving them exclusive rights to use and commercialize their inventions for a specified period. They are an important indicator of research and innovation output.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(527,'What is intellectual property rights (IPR)?','Intellectual Property Rights (IPR) protect the creations of the mind, such as inventions, designs, and artistic works. They ensure that creators receive recognition and financial benefits for their work.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(528,'What is the role of incubation centers in institutions?','Incubation centers support entrepreneurship by providing infrastructure, mentorship, and financial guidance to startups. They help students and faculty convert innovative ideas into viable business ventures.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(529,'What is entrepreneurship development in higher education?','Entrepreneurship development involves training and encouraging students to create, manage, and sustain business ventures. It focuses on developing skills such as innovation, risk-taking, leadership, and problem-solving, enabling students to become job creators rather than job seekers.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(530,'What are startups in the context of higher education?','Startups refer to newly established business ventures initiated by students or faculty based on innovative ideas. Institutions support startups through incubation centers, mentorship, funding assistance, and training programs to promote entrepreneurship.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(531,'What is the role of faculty in research and development?','Faculty play a key role in research and development by conducting research projects, publishing papers, guiding students, and contributing to innovation. They also collaborate with industries and institutions to enhance research output and academic quality.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(532,'What are faculty development programs (FDPs)?','Faculty Development Programs are training initiatives aimed at improving teaching skills, subject knowledge, research capabilities, and use of technology among faculty members. They ensure continuous professional growth and quality enhancement.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(533,'What are orientation and refresher courses?','Orientation and refresher courses are programs designed to update faculty on recent developments in their fields, teaching methodologies, and educational technologies. These programs help maintain academic standards and improve teaching effectiveness.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(534,'What is the importance of continuous professional development for teachers?','Continuous professional development ensures that teachers remain updated with new knowledge, technologies, and teaching strategies. It enhances their effectiveness, improves student learning outcomes, and contributes to overall institutional quality.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(535,'What is student-centric learning?','Student-centric learning focuses on active participation of students in the learning process. It encourages critical thinking, problem-solving, and personalized learning experiences, making education more engaging and effective.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(536,'What are experiential learning methods?','Experiential learning involves learning through direct experience, such as internships, fieldwork, projects, and practical activities. It helps students apply theoretical knowledge to real-world situations.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(537,'What is project-based learning?','Project-based learning is a teaching method where students gain knowledge and skills by working on real-life projects. It enhances teamwork, creativity, and problem-solving abilities.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(538,'What is participative learning?','Participative learning involves active engagement of students through discussions, group work, presentations, and collaborative activities. It promotes interaction, deeper understanding, and effective knowledge sharing.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(539,'What is the importance of ICT in teaching and learning?','Information and Communication Technology (ICT) plays a crucial role in enhancing teaching and learning by providing digital tools, online resources, and interactive platforms. It improves access to information, supports innovative teaching methods such as e-learning and virtual classrooms, and makes education more flexible and engaging for students.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(540,'What are e-learning resources?','E-learning resources include digital materials such as e-books, online lectures, videos, learning management systems, and virtual labs. These resources support self-paced learning and provide students with easy access to educational content anytime and anywhere.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(541,'What is a Learning Management System (LMS)?','A Learning Management System (LMS) is a software platform used to manage, deliver, and track educational courses and training programs. It facilitates online learning, assignment submission, assessments, and communication between teachers and students.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(542,'What is the role of libraries in higher education?','Libraries support academic activities by providing access to books, journals, research papers, and digital resources. They play a vital role in promoting reading habits, supporting research, and facilitating knowledge acquisition.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(543,'What are digital libraries?','Digital libraries are online collections of academic resources such as e-books, journals, databases, and multimedia content. They provide remote access to information and support modern learning and research needs.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(544,'What is INFLIBNET?','INFLIBNET (Information and Library Network) is an initiative that provides access to a wide range of academic resources, including e-journals and databases, to higher education institutions in India. It supports research and learning through digital connectivity.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(545,'What is e-ShodhSindhu?','e-ShodhSindhu is a consortium that provides access to e-journals, e-books, and databases for academic institutions. It helps researchers and students access high-quality scholarly content.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(546,'What is the role of laboratories in education?','Laboratories provide practical exposure and hands-on experience to students. They help in understanding theoretical concepts through experiments and enhance scientific and technical skills.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(547,'What is IT infrastructure in institutions?','IT infrastructure includes hardware, software, networking systems, and digital tools that support academic and administrative activities. It enables efficient communication, data management, and technology-based learning.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(548,'What is maintenance of infrastructure?','Maintenance of infrastructure involves regular upkeep, repair, and upgrading of physical and digital facilities to ensure their effective functioning. Proper maintenance supports a conducive learning environment and long-term sustainability.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(549,'What is student support in higher education?','Student support refers to the services and facilities provided by institutions to ensure the academic success and well-being of students. These include scholarships, counseling, mentoring, career guidance, and financial assistance, which help students overcome challenges and achieve their goals.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(550,'What are scholarships and financial assistance?','Scholarships and financial assistance are monetary supports provided to students based on merit, need, or specific criteria. They help students continue their education without financial barriers and promote equal opportunities.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(551,'What is student counseling?','Student counseling provides guidance and support to students in dealing with academic, personal, and psychological issues. It helps improve mental well-being, decision-making, and overall development.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(552,'What is mentoring system in institutions?','A mentoring system involves assigning faculty members to guide students in academic and personal matters. Mentors monitor student progress, provide advice, and help in achieving academic and career goals.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(553,'What is career guidance and placement support?','Career guidance and placement support include training programs, workshops, internships, and recruitment drives that prepare students for employment. Institutions assist students in developing skills required for job opportunities and higher studies.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(554,'What is student progression?','Student progression refers to the advancement of students to higher education, employment, or entrepreneurship after completing their studies. It is an important indicator of institutional effectiveness.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(555,'What is alumni association?','An alumni association is a network of former students who stay connected with the institution. Alumni contribute through mentoring, funding, networking, and sharing professional experiences with current students.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(556,'What is student participation in governance?','Student participation in governance involves including students in decision-making processes through committees and councils. It ensures transparency, accountability, and representation of student interests.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(557,'What are extracurricular activities?','Extracurricular activities include sports, cultural events, clubs, and competitions that support the overall development of students beyond academics. They help build leadership, teamwork, and social skills.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(558,'What is student welfare?','Student welfare includes all measures taken to ensure the safety, health, and well-being of students. It includes facilities such as hostels, medical services, grievance redressal systems, and support services.','ssr','university',NULL,NULL),(559,'What is the minimum percentage of new courses that must be introduced over a five-year period to achieve the highest score of 4?','To achieve the highest benchmark score of 4, an institution must introduce at least 20% or more new courses over a period of five years. This reflects the institution’s commitment to curriculum innovation, adaptability to industry requirements, and alignment with emerging knowledge areas. Regular updating of courses ensures that students receive relevant and up-to-date education.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(560,'If a university introduces exactly 12% of new courses, what would its benchmark score be?','A university introducing 12% new courses falls within the 10%–20% range, which corresponds to a score of  This indicates moderate curriculum revision efforts, showing that the institution is updating its courses but still has room for improvement to reach the highest level.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(561,'To avoid receiving a score of 0, what is the minimum percentage of new courses required?','The institution must introduce at least 5% new courses. If the percentage is below this threshold, it indicates stagnation in curriculum development and results in a score of 0, meaning no meaningful academic innovation has taken place.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(562,'How many certificate/diploma/online courses are needed to achieve a score of 3?','To secure a score of 3, an institution should offer between 10 and 20 certificate, diploma, or online courses (such as SWAYAM or NPTEL) where students are actively enrolled and benefiting. This shows a balanced effort toward skill enhancement beyond the core curriculum.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(563,'If an institution has implemented 15 such courses, what score does it get?','With 15 courses, the institution clearly falls in the 10–20 range, which corresponds to a score of  This indicates satisfactory engagement in offering additional learning opportunities.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(564,'What percentage of programmes must include practical components for a score of 4?','For the highest score, at least 50% or more of programmes must include practical components such as internships, fieldwork, or research projects. This ensures that students gain hands-on experience and industry exposure.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(565,'What percentage range is required for a score of 2?','A score of 2 is awarded when 20%–30% of programmes include practical components. This reflects limited practical exposure, indicating the need for further improvement.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(566,'Which stakeholders must feedback be collected from (besides students and teachers)?','Apart from students and teachers, feedback must also be collected from employers, alumni, and parents. These stakeholders provide diverse perspectives about curriculum relevance, employability, and institutional effectiveness.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(567,'What is required to achieve Classification ‘‘A’’?','If no action is taken after analysis, the institution receives Classification C with a score of 2, indicating incomplete feedback implementation.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(568,'Difference between Classification B and A?','Classification B includes collection, analysis, and communication of feedback, whereas Classification A additionally requires implementation of improvements and public disclosure of actions taken.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(569,'Metric 1: What is the minimum enrollment percentage required for an institution to receive a score of 2?','To receive a score of 2 under this metric, the institution must achieve an enrollment percentage between 70% and 80%. This shows that a significant number of available seats are filled, indicating moderate demand for the institution’s programs. However, it is not considered excellent performance, as higher scores require nearly full enrollment.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(570,'Metric 2: To achieve a score of 4, what percentage of seats must be filled against reserved categories (SC, ST, OBC, etc.) according to the applicable reservation policy?','To achieve the highest score of 4, the institution must ensure that 100% of seats reserved for SC, ST, OBC, and other categories are filled according to government reservation policies. This demonstrates strong commitment to inclusivity and social justice in admissions.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(571,'Metric 2: If an institution fills less than 40% of its reserved category seats for the first-year admission, what score is assigned?','If less than 40% of reserved category seats are filled, the institution receives a score of  This reflects poor adherence to reservation norms and lack of inclusiveness.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(572,'Metric 2: What is the required student-to-full-time teacher ratio to achieve the highest benchmark score of 4?','To achieve a score of 4, the student-to-teacher ratio must be 20:1 or lower. This ensures better interaction between students and teachers, improved attention to individual learners, and higher quality of education.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(573,'Metric 2: If the student-to-teacher ratio is greater than 60:1, what score does the institution receive?','If the student-to-teacher ratio exceeds 60:1, the institution receives a score of  Such a high ratio indicates overcrowded classrooms and poor teaching effectiveness.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(574,'Metric 1: What percentage of full-time teachers must be appointed against sanctioned posts during the last five years to earn a score of 3?','To earn a score of 3, the institution must have 70% to 80% of full-time teaching positions filled against sanctioned posts. This shows adequate staffing levels but still leaves room for improvement.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(575,'Metric 2: To reach a score of 4, what is the required percentage of full-time teachers holding a Ph.D., D.M., M.Ch., or D.N.B Super specialty?','To achieve a score of 4, at least 80% or more of full-time teachers must hold a Ph.D. or equivalent qualification. This indicates strong academic expertise and research capability.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(576,'Metric 3: How many years of average teaching experience are required for full-time teachers to qualify for a score of 1?','An average teaching experience of 2 to 5 years is required to qualify for a score of  This represents a basic level of experience but not sufficient for higher scores.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(577,'Metric 1: What is the specific range of days for result declaration (from the end of exams) that results in a score of 3?','To achieve a score of 3, results must be declared within 15 to 30 days after the completion of examinations. This indicates a reasonably efficient evaluation system.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(578,'Metric 2: What is the maximum allowable percentage of student complaints or grievances regarding evaluation to still receive a score of 4?','To receive a score of 4, the percentage of student grievances must be less than 1%. This reflects a fair and transparent evaluation process with minimal disputes.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(579,'Metric 3: What is the primary difference between Option B and Option C regarding the automation of the Examination division?','Option B represents partial automation where several processes are computerized, while Option C represents limited automation where most processes are still manual with minimal digital support.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(580,'Metric 3: Which option describes an Examination division that utilizes only manual methodology?','Option D describes a fully manual examination system with no automation.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(581,'Metric 2: To achieve a score of 4, the pass percentage of students (excluding backlogs) must be at or above what threshold?','To achieve the highest score, the pass percentage must be 90% or above. This indicates strong academic performance and effective teaching-learning processes.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(582,'Metric 2: If the pass percentage of students is between 60% and 70%, what benchmark score is assigned?','If the pass percentage is between 60% and 70%, the institution receives a score of 2, indicating average academic performance.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(583,'Metric 1: According to the source, what is the format through which the Student Satisfaction Survey regarding the teaching-learning process must be conducted?','The Student Satisfaction Survey must be conducted in an online format. This ensures transparency, ease of participation, and efficient analysis of responses.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(584,'Metric 2: How much average seed money (in INR Lakhs) must an institution provide annually to its teachers to achieve the highest score of 4?','To achieve a score of 4, the institution must provide more than ₹25 lakhs per year as seed money to its teachers. This financial support encourages faculty to initiate research projects, publish papers, and develop innovative ideas, thereby strengthening the research culture of the institution.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(585,'Metric 3: To earn a score of 2, what is the required percentage of teachers receiving national or international fellowships or financial support for advanced studies?','To earn a score of 2, around 5% to 10% of teachers must receive fellowships or financial support. This indicates some level of encouragement for faculty development, but not at a highly satisfactory level.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(586,'Metric 4: What percentage of JRFs, SRFs, and other research fellows among enrolled PhD scholars is necessary to qualify for a score of 3?','To qualify for a score of 3, approximately 40% to 60% of enrolled PhD scholars should be receiving fellowships such as JRF or SRF. This reflects a healthy research environment with adequate financial support.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(587,'Metric 1: What is the total research funding threshold (in INR Lakhs) from government and non-government sources over five years required to reach a score of 4?','To reach a score of 4, the institution must secure more than ₹500 lakhs in research funding over five years. This shows strong research capability and recognition from funding agencies.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(588,'Metric 2: How many research projects per teacher must be funded by government or international bodies to receive a benchmark score of 1?','To receive a score of 1, the institution must have at least 02 funded projects per teacher. This indicates minimal participation in funded research activities.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(589,'Metric 2: How many awards for research or innovations must the institution, its teachers, or its students receive to achieve a score of 3?','To achieve a score of 3, the institution should receive 10 to 20 awards for research or innovation. This reflects recognition at a moderate level.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(590,'Metric 1: The institution is evaluated on its Code of Ethics for research through four implementation methods. Which Option (A–E) corresponds to having all four of these methods in place?','Option A corresponds to having all four ethical practices implemented, such as plagiarism checks, ethics committees, and adherence to research guidelines, ensuring integrity in research activities.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(591,'Metric 3: To receive a score of 4, how many Ph.Ds must be awarded per recognized guide during the last five years?','To receive a score of 4, each recognized guide must have produced at least 8 Ph.D scholars over the last five years, indicating strong research supervision.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(592,'Metric 4: What is the required average number of research papers published per teacher to earn a score of 2?','To earn a score of 2, each teacher must publish around 2 to 4 research papers in recognized journals. This reflects average research output.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(593,'Metric 5: How many books or chapters in edited volumes must be published per teacher to qualify for a score of 1?','At least one book or chapter per teacher must be published to qualify for a score of 1, indicating basic academic contribution.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(594,'Metric 6: There are six platforms listed for e-content development. How many of these must be utilized by teachers to receive Option B?','To receive Option B, teachers must utilize at least four platforms for e-content development, showing significant engagement with digital teaching tools.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(595,'Metric 1: If an institution generates between 150 and 200 Lakhs from consultancy and corporate training over five years, what benchmark score is assigned?','If the institution generates ₹150 to ₹200 lakhs, it is awarded a score of 3, indicating good consultancy performance.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(596,'Metric 1: What is the minimum revenue required to avoid a score of 0 for consultancy?','The institution must generate at least ₹50 lakhs to avoid a score of  Anything below this reflects very low consultancy engagement.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(597,'Metric 2: How many extension and outreach programs must be conducted by the institution over the last five years to reach a score of 4?','To achieve a score of 4, the institution must conduct more than 100 outreach programs, demonstrating strong community engagement.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(598,'Metric 1: To achieve a score of 3, how many functional MoUs or linkages must the university have?','To achieve a score of 3, the institution should have around 30 to 50 active MoUs, reflecting moderate collaboration with industries and organizations.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(599,'Metric 2: To achieve the highest score of 4, what minimum percentage of expenditure must be dedicated to infrastructure development over five years?','More than 30% of total expenditure (excluding salary) must be spent on infrastructure development to achieve a score of 4, indicating strong investment in facilities.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(600,'Metric 2: If an institution\'s expenditure on infrastructure augmentation is 25%, which benchmark score will it receive?','If the expenditure is 25%, the institution receives a score of 3, showing good but not highest investment.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(601,'Metric 2: What is the specific percentage range required to earn a score of 1 for this metric?','A 10% to 20% expenditure range qualifies for a score of 1, indicating minimal investment.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(602,'Metric 2: What is the required percentage of expenditure for books and journals to reach a score of 4?','To achieve a score of 4, the institution must spend more than 10% of its budget on books, e-books, and journals.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(603,'Metric 2: If a university spends 7% of its budget, what is its corresponding benchmark score?','If 7% is spent, the institution receives a score of 3, reflecting adequate library investment.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(604,'Metric 2: To avoid a score of 0, the expenditure must be at least what percentage?','At least 2% expenditure is required to avoid a score of ','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(605,'Metric 2: What is the ideal student-to-computer ratio required to achieve a score of 4?','The ideal ratio is 5:1 or better, ensuring sufficient access to computing facilities.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(606,'Metric 2: If the student-to-computer ratio is 20:1, what benchmark score is assigned?','A ratio of 20:1 corresponds to a score of 2, indicating limited access.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(607,'Metric 3: To qualify for Option A, how many of the listed facilities must the institution possess?','To qualify for Option A, the institution must have 10 to 11 facilities, showing comprehensive infrastructure.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(608,'Metric 3: If an institution has five facilities, which Option letter and score does it receive?','With five facilities, the institution receives Option C with a score of ','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(609,'Metric 3: Which specific facility is listed as option number 2 for developing e-content and other resources?','The facility listed as option number 2 is Media Studio, which supports content creation and digital learning resources.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(610,'Metric 1: What percentage of expenditure must be incurred on the maintenance of physical and academic support facilities (excluding salary) to earn a score of 4?','To earn a score of 4, the institution must spend more than 30% of its total expenditure (excluding salary) on the maintenance of physical and academic facilities. This indicates strong commitment to sustaining infrastructure quality, ensuring that laboratories, classrooms, and other facilities remain functional and up to date.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(611,'Metric 1: If the maintenance expenditure is between 10% and 20%, what benchmark score is awarded?','If the maintenance expenditure falls between 10% and 20%, the institution receives a score of  This reflects moderate maintenance efforts, but not sufficient for higher benchmarks.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(612,'Metric 1: What is the minimum expenditure percentage required to receive a score of 1?','The minimum expenditure required to receive a score of 1 is around 5%. This indicates very basic maintenance activities.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(613,'Metric 1: What is the minimum percentage of students that must benefit from scholarships and freeships to achieve the highest score of 4?','To achieve a score of 4, more than 70% of students must benefit from scholarships, freeships, or financial assistance. This reflects strong institutional support for student welfare and inclusiveness.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(614,'Metric 1: If between 40% and 50% of students benefit from such financial support, what benchmark score is assigned?','If 40% to 50% of students benefit, the institution receives a score of 2, indicating moderate support for students.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(615,'Metric 3: How many capacity development and skills enhancement initiatives must an institution undertake to qualify for Option B?','To qualify for Option B, the institution must implement at least three out of the four initiatives, such as soft skills, language and communication skills, life skills, and ICT/computing skills.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(616,'Metric 3: Which specific skills are categorized under \"Life skills\" in this metric?','Life skills include communication skills, teamwork, problem-solving ability, leadership qualities, adaptability, and decision-making skills. These are essential for personal and professional development.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(617,'Metric 4: To receive an \'A\' rating for the redressal of student grievances, how many implementation mechanisms must the institution adopt?','To receive an \'A\' rating, the institution must implement all four mechanisms, such as grievance redressal committees, anti-ragging measures, sexual harassment prevention cells, and transparent complaint systems.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(618,'Metric 1: What percentage of placement for outgoing students is required over the last five years to earn a score of 2?','To earn a score of 2, the institution must achieve around 30% to 40% placement of outgoing students. This indicates average performance in student placement.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(619,'Metric 2: To achieve a score of 4, what percentage of graduated students must have progressed to higher education?','To achieve a score of 4, more than 50% of graduating students must progress to higher education. This reflects strong academic orientation and student aspirations for advanced learning.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(620,'Metric 2: If the percentage of students progressing to higher education is less than 5%, what is the assigned benchmark score?','If less than 5% of students progress to higher education, the institution receives a score of 0, indicating very poor academic progression.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(621,'Metric 3: What is the required percentage of students qualifying in state, national, or international examinations to reach a score of 3?','To reach a score of 3, about 10% to 20% of students must qualify in competitive examinations such as NET, SLET, or UPSC.','benchmark','university',NULL,NULL),(622,'Metric 1: How many awards or medals are needed to qualify for a score of 3?','To qualify for a score of 3, the institution must secure around 10 to 20 awards or medals in s